<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Government Bonds: Spanish prices tumble as investor
confidence wanes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPANISH government bond prices fell sharply yesterday, as the peseta's slide
undermined confidence among international investors.
Although the bond market opened quite strongly, prices dropped when the
Spanish central bank failed to intervene to support the currency at Pta72
against the D-Mark. However, most analysts still expect the Spanish
government to stay within the exchange rate mechanism, despite pressing
economic problems, particularly unemployment.
There was some speculation yesterday that the authorities might try to cut
rates and allow the peseta to drift to the bottom of its band. But such a
move could prompt greater pressure on the currency.
THE Italian bond market also performed poorly yesterday, shedding  1/4
point, as fears over the political situation persisted. Dealers were
concerned that the cabinet shuffle over the weekend had not addressed some
of the deeper problems.
Expectations of a vote of confidence in the next few weeks are expected to
continue to depress prices.
THE bund market again benefited from a flight to quality, continuing its
rally, although further interest rate cuts have already been discounted.
Bund contracts on both the London International Financial Futures &amp; Options
Exchange and the Deutsche Terminborse broke through resistance levels. But
dealers said the latest improvement was sparked more by switching than by
outright buying.
INVESTORS in Spanish and Italian bonds were seen switching into Dutch,
French and Danish paper, as well as bunds, partly based on expectations of
interest rate cuts.
The Danish bond market was the strongest performer of the day, gaining a
full point. Dutch bonds also closed sharply higher, supported by strong
domestic buying. The 10-year bond broke through a resistance level at 6 3/4
per cent as the market's rally persisted.
UK gilt prices ended virtually unchanged in lacklustre trading yesterday.
Slightly stronger than expected GDP data failed to impress traders, who were
disappointed that last week's gilts tap totalling Pounds 1.2bn was still not
fully sold.
LONGER-dated US Treasury prices turned sharply higher yesterday afternoon
pushing the 30-year bond's yield to a record low.
The benchmark 30-year government bond had a yield of 6.931 per cent in late
trading, its lowest level since the issue was first sold to the public in
1997. The long bond was quoted  7/8 higher at 102 5/16 . Movement was less
dramatic at the short end of the market, where the two-year note firmed
1/32 to yield 3.927 per cent.
In the absence of important economic news yesterday, the market remained
focused on President Bill Clinton's deficit reduction package. Some players
remain enthusiastic about his willingness to tackle the federal deficit,
along with measures which should slow the rate of economic growth in 1994,
But others were concerned that spending cuts might not be sufficient to keep
inflation in check.
The Federal Reserve entered the open market to arrange Dollars 2.5bn of
customer repurchase agreements when Fed funds were trading at 3 per cent.
There was also some positioning ahead of today's Dollars 15.25bn two-year
note auction and tomorrow's Dollars 11bn five-year note auction.
</TEXT>
