FT  23 FEB 93 / International Company News: Nordstrom profit edges ahead in
final term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORDSTROM, the Seattle-based retailer, yesterday reported after-tax profits
of Dollars 49.96m in the final three months to end-January.
The results were scored on a 9.3 per cent improvement in sales, at Dollars
1.07bn, and compared with a net profit of Dollars 40.86m in the
corresponding period of 1991-92.
The 1992-93 results would have been slightly higher, had it not been for a
Dollars 4m charge related to the payment of certain plaintiffs' legal fees
in Nordstrom's recent settlement of a labour class action lawsuit.
Nordstrom's shares, listed on the over-the-counter market, rallied Dollars 1
7/8 on the news, to Dollars 38 3/4 .
As with most retailers, the fourth 'holiday' quarter is the most crucial
within the trading year.
In the case of Nordstrom - a family-run, upmarket fashion retailer which
grew rapidly in the late 1980s but where progress has stalled recently - the
final quarter's figures take the full-year profits total to Dollars 136.6m
after tax.
In the previous year, the company recorded profits of Dollars 135.8m. Annual
sales were Dollars 3.42bn, compared with Dollars 3.18bn in 1991-2.
