<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Halifax chief executive named
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALIFAX Building Society has completed an eight-month search for a new chief
executive by appointing Mr Mike Blackburn (right), chief executive of the
Leeds Permanent Building Society, to take over in August.
Mr Blackburn, chief executive of the Leeds for the past five years, has
attracted controversy by criticising aspects of government policy. He will
take over at the Halifax when Mr Jim Birrell, the current chief executive,
retires at 60.
The appointment of a new chief executive of Halifax has been the subject of
much speculation as it is the largest society with assets of Pounds 59bn and
it appointed a firm of headhunters last June to aid its search.
Mr Jon Foulds, Halifax chairman, was thought to have been seeking an
outsider to ensure innovation. Mr Blackburn is respected for having improved
Leeds' performance since he joined it from the Access Joint Credit Card
Company.
Mr Foulds said yesterday that Mr Blackburn was 'ideally placed to build on
the culture and values' of the Halifax. He said Mr Blackburn would be
'working with an excellent management team and going forward from an
enviable base'.
Mr Blackburn is to leave the Leeds, the fifth biggest society with assets of
Pounds 16.2bn, at the end of this week and will probably join the Halifax
this summer.
Leeds announced that Mr Roger Boyes, finance director, would take over as
acting chief executive from March 1. The board is expected to consider
whether to make the appointment permanent after that.
Observer, Page 19
