<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Branson gives BA 24 hours to settle over 'dirty tricks'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR RICHARD Branson, the head of Virgin Atlantic, yesterday gave British
Airways 24 hours to settle their 'dirty tricks' battle.
Mr Branson wants BA to agree compensation for the damage inflicted on his
airline by BA's campaign or face the threat of renewed legal action.
Meanwhile, BA said last night that it would look into allegations made on
ITN that airline employees in Los Angeles had continued to try to poach
Virgin passengers after the airline had pledged not to do so again.
Virgin has previously set deadlines as part of its tactics to reach an early
settlement with BA, following last month's Pounds 610,000 libel victory
against its competitor. But on each occasion it has been prepared to let
talks continue after the expiry of the deadline in the hope of a
breakthrough.
The smaller airline, however, last night appeared poised to break off talks
and carry out its threat to pursue its claims of anti-competitive activities
against BA through the courts.
Speaking at Heathrow airport at the opening of a new departure lounge for
Virgin passengers, Mr Branson said that, without progress towards an
agreement over the next 24 hours, 'there is no point in carrying on'.
He added: 'We lost a great deal of money because of their tactics and need
compensation. We don't want to see things dragged on indefinitely but they
are repeatedly delaying a solution to the problem.'
Last night, BA said it had agreed to make no comment on the talks and that
it did not intend to respond to Mr Branson's remarks.
Talks began three weeks ago in an atmosphere of optimism, involving Mr Sid
Pennington, managing director of Virgin Atlantic, Mr Trevor Abbott,
financial adviser to Mr Branson and Mr Robert Ayling, BA's newly-appointed
group managing director.
But relations between the two sides deteriorated a week ago, following the
disclosure of a letter from BA to Virgin setting out proposals to settle the
dispute. Virgin said the terms - which included a Pounds 3m payment - were
not acceptable.
Virgin has said throughout that it will consider mounting anti-competitive
cases against BA in the US and Europe unless compensation can be agreed.
The allegations that BA is continuing to try to poach Virgin passengers
centred on statements from a Los Angeles-based travel agent that BA staff,
under the mistaken impression that he was a Virgin passenger, had attempted
to persuade him to switch flights to BA.
</TEXT>
