<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government seeks summer approval
for Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is determined to secure ratification of the Maastricht treaty
by the summer, despite the emergence last night of fresh confusion over the
possible consequences of new amendments relating to the social chapter.
Senior ministers believe the legislation can receive parliamentary approval
before the summer recess and would be prepared to see parliament sitting
into August to hasten ratification. Normally both the Commons and the Lords
would break up for the summer in late July, returning in October to tie up
loose ends.
Yesterday, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl warned that at least 10 European
countries would go ahead with their unity plans if either Britain or Denmark
failed to endorse the Maastricht treaty within six months.
Mr Kohl's statement reiterated a position he outlined at the European
Community summit in Edinburgh last December and officials in both Bonn and
Downing Street sought to play down the impact of Mr Kohl's words.
But the Maastricht bill hit a further snag yesterday as hours of debate were
lost in a renewed row over the government's U-turn last week on the legal
effect of passing an opposition amendment on the social chapter.
And in seeking to explain the government's position to a noisy and crowded
Commons, Sir Nicholas Lyell, attorney-general, appeared to admit the
possibility of more disruption as a result of fresh social chapter-related
amendments.
Labour will now turn its attention to an amendment which would exclude the
social protocol from the part of the bill giving the European parliament
more powers.
Though Sir Nicholas seemed to suggest that if such an amendment were passed
it could wreck the ratification process, that has not ruled it out so far as
the Labour front bench is concerned.
The opposition has time to decide on tactics. But such an amendment offers
the most likely prospect of an effective alliance between the opposition and
Tory Euro-rebels against the government.
Yesterday's hiccup came as Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said the
government would have the authority to meet the administrative costs of the
social chapter for which Britain could be liable.
In a letter to Sir Teddy Taylor, MP for Southend East and a leading Tory
Euro-sceptic, Mr Hurd said parliament's assent to the Maastricht bill at the
third reading would enable the government to ratify the treaty. 'That
includes the social protocol and Britain's obligation to pay its share of
associated administrative costs.'
In the Commons, Sir Nicholas underlined the government's insistence that
defeat on the original Labour amendment would not wreck the treaty, arguing
there was 'no constitutional impropriety' in proceeding with ratification
under such circumstances.
'Parliament cannot pick and choose which treaty obligations to accept,' he
said. 'But it can prevent ratification of the entire treaty by refusing to
enact the bill.'
He declined requests for his advice on the legal effect of passing the
amendment to be published, saying he was not aware of any precedent.
</TEXT>
