<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Crime grates on the electorate's
raw nerve - Signs of a limited consensus seen between the two main parties
on law and order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH unbridled chutzpah Mr Tony Blair, the shadow home secretary, wrote last
night to the Home Office suggesting that his document, Getting to Grips with
Youth Crime, could form the basis of government policy.
It would be churlish of Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, to throw it
straight in the bin.
Labour and the Tories are at one on several points. They agree that tackling
juvenile crime has to be a priority, the government has to take a lead in
ensuring the community distinguishes between 'right' and 'wrong', and that
offenders beyond redemption should be locked away.
But to state that much is far from spotting an outbreak of consensus. The
political noises and the apparent sparks of originality on crime policy -
intensified by last week's murder of a two-year-old in Liverpool - reflect
more a shift in the centre of gravity in the debate on law and order.
Mr Blair, a very able frontbencher appointed to his present post last
summer, has taken a policy area in which Labour is traditionally weak.
Extending the work of his predecessor, Mr Roy Hattersley, he has put a
greater emphasis on part of the party's message that matches the convictions
of Labour's target voters - the middle classes and aspiring working classes:
that crime is bad, criminals are nasty and something has to be done.
Although a connection is denied, Mr Blair has echoed President Bill Clinton
to the extent that he is enunciating what a majority of the population - and
the electorate - believes. The message is two-pronged, however, for Labour
has not abandoned its long-held belief that addressing causes is as
important as condemning criminals. 'We need to tackle this problem in a
concerted way; tough on crime, tough on the causes of crime,' Mr Blair said
at the launch of the policy document.
So while Mr Blair backed more secure accommodation for teenage offenders and
agreed there may be a gap in the law that prevents persistent young
offenders being imprisoned, he also wanted measures to cut drug abuse and
improve education.
He opposed the setting up of private-sector-operated special institutions
for young offenders, preferring instead an expansion of the secure homes run
by local authorities under the health department's budget. Similarly, Mr
Blair used a speech last Friday to emphasise the importance of morality, but
stressed that 'the breakdown in order is intimately linked to the break-up
of community.'
He is adept at exploiting Tory weaknesses. After 14 years in power, the
debate among Conservatives is becoming more fluid. The rightwing 'hanging
and flogging' MPs remain, pressing Mr Clarke last night to take strong
action soon. Some now openly call for the castration of rapists. Many
support corporal punishment.
But Mr Clarke recognises the need for the government to 'lead society' and
of giving youngsters a sense of purpose.
Concepts of 'society' and 'community' are returning to ministers' speeches.
Mr Brian Mawhinney, the health minister, will tomorrow urge churches to take
more of a role in educating people in social issues such as Aids.
There is a sense of failure. Initiatives have been and gone, but the crime
rate has risen inexorably. 'Beware of politicians who speak loudly on crime.
They promise a lot and do little,' said Sir John Wheeler, former Tory
chairman of the Commons home affairs committee. Many of the Tory
backbenchers fear the party is in danger of losing still more political
ground over law-and-order issues to Labour.
Amid this maelstrom, Mr Clarke is trying to agree details of his juvenile
crime initiative and respond to pressure for action from Tory ranks. A
crackdown against persistent teenage offenders was announced at last
October's Conservative conference. Promises of tougher penalties for
offences committed on bail were in the Tory election manifesto last April.
But parliamentary time for the necessary legislation unlikely until the
autumn, has still to be agreed.
If Mr Clarke does not fill the vacuum, Mr Blair will not be afraid of trying
himself.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P91   Executive, Legislative and General Government.
</IN>
