<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Warning on police reforms
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
NO SIGNIFICANT structural or constitutional changes should be made to the
police service without a Royal Commission or independent inquiry, police
authority members said yesterday.
About 200 representatives from county councils and metropolitan authorities
met at the House of Commons to discuss reform proposals.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, has indicated he is considering
radical changes that could include reducing the number of forces in England
and Wales from 43 to about 25, centralising funding and replacing locally
elected councillors on police authorities with nominees.
But Mr John Smith, vice-president of the Association of Chief Police
Officers, said elected members should remain a 'significant' proportion of
authorities.
</TEXT>
