<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Ulster MP survives legal challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEGAL attempt to oust West Belfast MP Dr Joe Hendron failed yesterday
after judges at a special election court in the city ruled that he had made
inaccurate election returns but was not guilty of corrupt practice.
At the general election last April, Dr Hendron captured the seat for the
nationalist Social Democratic and Labour party by 589 votes from Mr Gerry
Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing. Mr Adams had held
the seat since 1983.
After the election, Dr Hendron estimated that he was helped by about 1,500
Protestants in unionist enclaves of the constituency who had voted
tactically to remove Mr Adams.
In the legal challenge resolved yesterday, a West Belfast constituent had
alleged that Dr Hendron's campaign had overspent on the legal limit of
Pounds 6,375.
If the court had found that either Dr Hendron or his election agent had
acted illegally or corruptly, the Speaker of the Commons would have been
recommended to disqualify Dr Hendron for up to 10 years and a by-election
would have been required.
After the ruling, Dr Hendron said he felt as if he had 'won the election all
over again', and that he and his agent had been 'totally and absolutely
vindicated by the court'.
But they now face a Pounds 40,000 legal bill after the judges made a special
ruling ordering that the parties in the case pay their own costs.
In making the order the judges also said: 'We consider that there were
matters to be properly investigated in this election court and the party
(who took the action) was fully justified in making this petition, and we
think it proper that this should be recognised.'
</TEXT>
