<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Senior GMTV executive resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MS LIS HOWELL, director of programmes at GMTV, yesterday became a casualty
of the commercial breakfast company's disappointing performance in the
ratings.
Her resignation comes less than two months after GMTV took over the
franchise from TV-am. It follows the appointment of Mr Greg Dyke, former
chief executive of London Weekend Television, as non-executive chairman.
Ms Howell will be replaced by Mr Peter McHugh, a former head of current
affairs at Tyne Tees television.
The latest ratings show that GMTV is not very far ahead of its two rivals,
BBC Breakfast News, and Channel 4's The Big Breakfast.
GMTV has been getting a weekday peak audience of 1.7m with a 1.1m average,
15 per cent below its expected audience. The BBC, which has a harder news
format, has a peak of 1.3m viewers and an average of 850,000.
The big surprise has been the low-budget success of The Big Breakfast which
has been winning a peak audience of 1.2m and an average figure of 650,000.
The Big Breakfast has an annual budget of about Pounds 8m compared with
annual programme costs of around Pounds 30m at GMTV.
On Friday Mr Dyke emphasised there was no crisis comparable with the early
days of TV-am.
Mr Christopher Stoddart, managing director, said then that there was
'plentiful demand for advertising'. GMTV, jointly owned by Carlton
Communications, LWT (Holdings), Scottish TV, Walt Disney and The Guardian
and Manchester Evening News, took or booked more than Pounds 50m in
advertising revenue before it went on air on January 1.
