<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Labour targets Welsh valleys
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday launched an initiative aimed at reviving the south Wales
valleys.
Mr Ron Davies, shadow Welsh secretary, backed by 12 Welsh Labour MPs, called
for a strategy to improve workforce skills, introduce more technology and
lift wages. He said: 'A twin-track programme is needed: immediate action to
halt the economic decline and a longer-term, more strategic programme geared
to permanent recovery.'
Labour believes the government's valleys programme has failed to produce
lasting economic improvements. Mr Davies said the scheme had 'upgraded the
property and environment of the valleys. They are greener, but no
foundations have been built for durable local economies.'
The initiative is an attempt to steal thunder from the government, which is
on the point of introducing plans for the valleys, once dubbed 'Wales's only
area with inner-city-type problems'.
Lord Walker, when he was Welsh secretary, brought in the first valleys
programme in 1988. The initiative was continued by his successor Mr David
Hunt, who has promised to announce new measures before the present programme
expires at the end of March.
Labour believes the valleys should be feeder areas for the growing
industrial base being created along the M4 motorway corridor running
east-west across south Wales.
