<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / NHS chief in Scotland will head Oftel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE eight-month search for a new director-general for Oftel, the
telecommunications industry watchdog, ended yesterday with the appointment
of Mr Don Cruickshank, chief executive of the National Health Service in
Scotland.
The long-delayed appointment reflects the determination of Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to find a candidate with broad
business experience rather than a civil servant or academic. The post was
originally advertised at a salary of about Pounds 90,000 a year.
Confirming Mr Cruickshank's appointment from April 1, Mr Heseltine said
yesterday that the telecoms industry had changed significantly since
privatisation of British Telecommunications in 1984. The 1991 duopoly review
had triggered further liberalisation, and an increasing number of operators
had entered the market. He therefore wished to appoint someone 'who had
direct experience of competition as a businessman'.
Mr Cruickshank, a 50-year-old chartered accountant, became chief executive
of the NHS in Scotland in 1989. Before that, he was managing director of Mr
Richard Branson's Virgin group for five years. His career also includes a
period as commercial director of Times Newspapers, general manager of The
Sunday Times and a director of the information and entertainment division of
Pearson, owner of the Financial Times.
At the end of last year, there were suggestions that Mr Heseltine had
rejected all the names drawn up on a shortlist put to him and had ordered a
fresh search.
Mr Cruickshank will take over from Mr Bill Wigglesworth, who was made acting
director-general of Oftel following the departure last year of Sir Brian
Carsberg to head the Office of Fair Trading. Mr Wigglesworth will resume his
position as Oftel's deputy director-general.
Mr Cruickshank will arrive at Oftel after a period in which some important
decisions affecting the telecommunications industry have been taken,
particularly the duopoly review and the BT pricing formula which is set
until 1997.
Oftel is, however, charged with regulating the licences granted to the new
generation of competitors beginning to enter the telecommunications market.
Earlier this month, Ionica, a privately owned company and the first direct
competitor to BT and Mercury, was granted a licence which it hopes will give
it 5 per cent of the household and small-business market within 10 years. Up
to 30 more licence applications are being considered by the Department of
Trade and Industry.
Oftel is also awaiting a report on the future operation of the 999 emergency
services and is discussing with BT proposals for changes to its internal
accounting procedures.
</TEXT>
