<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / Yen soars to new highs on Bentsen comments: Tokyo stance on
currency linked to concern about rising trade surplus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO and KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE YEN surged to a new high against the dollar of Y116.85 in Tokyo
yesterday as the Japanese financial authorities showed little sign of
planning a concerted intervention to check its rise.
The sharp rise was mainly due to comments on Friday by Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US
treasury secretary, that he favoured a stronger yen, apparently to help
choke off the mounting Japanese trade surplus.
In New York, the dollar continued to react to Mr Bentsen's comments by
dropping below Friday's record low levels of Y118.20. Rumours that the
Japanese would intervene, despite their apparent lack of concern, reined in
the yen's rise and in late trading it was quoted at about Y116.30.
Early today Finance Minister Yoshiro Hayashi said Japan would act
appropriately to help stabilise the yen in the foreign exchange market, as
currency instability was bad for the global economy. The yen's rise would be
discussed at the Group of Seven finance ministers' and central bank
governors' meeting in London.
Economic Planning Agency Minister Hajime Funada also said he expected
Japan's monetary authorities to take 'appropriate steps'.
'I am concerned about the latest high yen trend which has been rather too
rapid,' Mr Funada said. 'I want to stress that it is desirable (for the yen)
to move gradually.'
Compared with the New York close the yen eased in morning trading in Tokyo
to about Y116.57.
The yen has risen by 6 per cent against the dollar in two weeks. While Tokyo
foreign exchange traders have scrambled to buy it, Japan's authorities have
engaged in a concerted display of calm over its ascent.
Foreign exchange traders were surprised at the government's low-profile
approach yesterday. In previous periods when the yen has appreciated
rapidly, most recently last autumn during the turmoil in European currency
markets, government officials maintained a daily commentary on the state of
the foreign exchange markets.
Yesterday, officials were still adopting a relaxed approach. Mr Hayashi said
there had been no specific steps against the yen's appreciation but he would
watch the exchange market closely.
Mr Yuji Tanahashi, vice international trade and industry minister, expressed
concern over the rapid rise, but said a dollar-yen rate of Y117 would be
acceptable.
Tokyo's willingness to see the yen appreciate is probably closely related to
its concern that its mounting trade surplus, which rose 34.9 per cent to
Dollars 5.3bn (Pounds 3.73bn) last month, might sour relations with the
Clinton administration.
Japan's leaders welcomed Mr Clinton's plans outlined last week to reduce the
US federal deficit. Japan has insisted that this has been one of the main
causes of the trade surplus.
By allowing the yen to rise, Japanese leaders are showing their willingness
to reciprocate with a macro-economic approach to reducing the trade surplus.
Japan wants to avoid a more segmented industry-by-industry approach.
Yet the surge may be short-lived, even though Tokyo economists belief the
yen could rise to Y115. The currency's rise has been prompted partly by
Japanese companies repatriating funds to improve their profits before they
close their books at the end of March. After that the demand for the yen
might tail off.
In the longer run, much will depend on the performance of the US economy.
While the Japanese economy is expected to remain sluggish until the autumn
at least, a sustained recovery in the US would strengthen the dollar.
Mr Geoffrey Barker, economist at Barings Securities in Tokyo, believes that
the yen could weaken to Y135 in the medium run.
The Bank of Japan yesterday played down the negative effects of the yen's
rise, saying the appreciation of the Japanese currency was not a pressing
economic concern as long as it was not rapid.
However, a stronger yen will hurt export-oriented motor and electronics
industries, already being battered by a plunge in domestic demand. Toyota
Motor says profits would be eroded by Y6bn (Pounds 36m) on a Y1 fall of the
dollar. Japanese life assurance companies, heavy investors in the US dollar
bond market, will also face losses on their portfolios.
The yen's appreciation, however, will help the country's banks, which need
to clear the capital-to-assets ratio set by the Bank for International
Settlements at the end of March, as the value of the banks' overseas assets
will fall relative to their yen capital base.
Other beneficiaries should include industries reliant on imports of raw
materials, such as paper and pulp companies and power utilities.
If the impact on Japanese industry is uncertain, the likely effect on
Japanese economic policy-making at home is easier to predict.
Manufacturing industry is already deeply depressed. Further pressure on
manufacturers' export margins would be extremely unwelcome.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
