<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / World Trade News: Clinton firm on Airbus subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday said he would seek 'tough new discipline'
on European subsidies to Airbus, while 'closely monitoring' an agreement
made last year by the Bush administration under which the Airbus governments
agreed to limit their 'aid' to the consortium.
In a speech to Boeing aircraft workers in Seattle, he expressed scepticism
about trade agreements. 'I've seen people promise us they'll do this, that
or the other thing, and then nothing ever happens.' It was the president's
second assault in two days on the hard-won Airbus pact, signed last summer.
In California, he complained that for the last several years, the US 'stood
by while Europe spent Dollars 26bn (Pounds 18.3bn) to develop Airbus to push
Americans out of work'.
Boeing's recent announcement that it would 28,000 workers redundant is only
partly due to defence cuts, he added. 'Boeing makes a lot of other planes,
too,' he said.
The president, in company with Vice-President Al Gore, also used the trip to
the west coast to announce the administration's technology programme and to
underscore his assertion that US trade policy must play an integral part in
economic policy.
Boeing has been making known its 'continued frustration' with Airbus and its
'competitive practices.' That President Clinton received the message was
evident in his statement two weeks ago at a televised 'town meeting'. He set
off alarms in Europe when he said he would not 'roll over and play dead'
over Airbus subsidies. It was not clear at the time if he knew that the
issue had been settled by his predecessor.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, last week said the Airbus
deal would be reviewed as part of a larger administration evaluation of
trade issues.
This exercise may well produce a clear departure from current policies, he
said.
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl yesterday said he was prepared to discuss the
issue with President Clinton, Reuter reports from New Delhi. 'What about
subsidies they give their arms industry, among others?' he said at the end
of a four-day visit to India.
</TEXT>
