<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 93 / US plans to drop relief supplies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US has decided to parachute relief supplies to blockaded Moslems in
eastern Bosnia, but President Bill Clinton is consulting with the United
Nations and western leaders before making the announcement, administration
officials said last night.
The officials said the airdrops under protection of US navy aircraft could
begin as early as this week, but no final timetable had been set.
Britain said yesterday it would not take part in an airdrop but was not
opposed to the US doing so.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, United Nations secretary general, said last night
that an airdrop must have UN authorisation.
Foreign Office officials in London said the US administration had not been
in touch with Britain on plans to parachute supplies.
'However, we have no problem with an operation of this kind if they want to
go ahead with it,' a spokesman said.
The lack of British enthusiasm for an airdrop is based on the advice of
defence officials that it would be dangerous and was unlikely to be
effective in the mountainous regions of eastern Bosnia.
By contrast, the officials stressed that Britain was taking an active part
in joint planning for a large-scale deployment of ground troops in Bosnia to
enforce a peace settlement, if and when such an agreement is reached.
The UN yesterday resumed its airlift to Sarajevo after city officials agreed
to distribute food throughout the Bosnian capital. The airlift was suspended
on February 12.
Major-Clinton talks, Page 5
